[src:raku-lang/metaprogramming] Metaprogramming can be used to move computations from runtime to compile time, to generate code using compile time computations, and to enable self-modifying code.
[src:raku-lang/metaprogramming] The ability of a programming language to be its own metalanguage allows reflective programming, and is termed *reflection*.
[src:raku-lang/metaprogramming] Reflection is a valuable language feature to facilitate metaprogramming.
[src:raku-lang/metaprogramming] Metaprogramming was popular in the 1970s and 1980s using list processing languages such as Lisp.
[src:raku-lang/metaprogramming] Lisp machine hardware gained some notice in the 1980s, and enabled applications that could process code.
[src:raku-lang/metaprogramming] They were often used for artificial intelligence applications.
[src:raku-lang/metaprogramming] Metaprogramming enables developers to write programs and develop code that falls under the generic programming paradigm.
[src:raku-lang/metaprogramming] Having the programming language itself as a first-class data type (as in Lisp, Prolog, SNOBOL, or Rebol) is also very useful; this is known as *homoiconicity*.
[src:raku-lang/metaprogramming] Generic programming invokes a metaprogramming facility within a language by allowing one to write code without the concern of specifying data types since they can be supplied as parameters when used.
[src:raku-lang/metaprogramming] Metaprogramming usually works in one of three ways.
[src:raku-lang/metaprogramming] The second approach is dynamic execution of expressions that contain programming commands, often composed from strings, but can also be from other methods using arguments or context, like JavaScript.
[src:raku-lang/metaprogramming] Thus, "programs can write programs." Although both approaches can be used in the same language, most languages tend to lean toward one or the other.
[src:raku-lang/metaprogramming] The third approach is to step outside the language entirely.
[src:raku-lang/metaprogramming] General purpose program transformation systems such as compilers, which accept language descriptions and carry out arbitrary transformations on those languages, are direct implementations of general metaprogramming.
[src:raku-lang/metaprogramming] This allows metaprogramming to be applied to virtually any target language without regard to whether that target language has any metaprogramming abilities of its own.
[src:raku-lang/metaprogramming] One can see this at work with Scheme and how it allows tackling some limits faced in C by using constructs that are part of the Scheme language to extend C.
[src:raku-lang/metaprogramming] Lisp is probably the quintessential language with metaprogramming facilities, both because of its historical precedence and because of the simplicity and power of its metaprogramming.
[src:raku-lang/metaprogramming] In Lisp metaprogramming, the unquote operator (typically a comma) introduces code that is evaluated at program definition time rather than at run time.
[src:raku-lang/metaprogramming] The metaprogramming language is thus identical to the host programming language, and existing Lisp routines can be directly reused for metaprogramming if desired.
[src:raku-lang/metaprogramming] This approach has been implemented in other languages by incorporating an interpreter in the program, which works directly with the program's data.
[src:raku-lang/metaprogramming] There are implementations of this kind for some common high-level languages, such as RemObjects’ Pascal Script for Object Pascal.
[src:raku-lang/metaprogramming] This script (or program) generates a new 993-line program that prints out the numbers 1–992.
[src:raku-lang/metaprogramming] This is only an illustration of how to use code to write more code; it is not the most efficient way to print out a list of numbers.
[src:raku-lang/metaprogramming] Nonetheless, a programmer can write and execute this metaprogram in less than a minute, and will have generated over 1000 lines of code in that amount of time.
[src:raku-lang/metaprogramming] A quine is a special kind of metaprogram that produces its own source code as its output.
[src:raku-lang/metaprogramming] Quines are generally of recreational or theoretical interest only.
[src:raku-lang/metaprogramming] Not all metaprogramming involves generative programming.
[src:raku-lang/metaprogramming] One style of generative approach is to employ domain-specific languages (DSLs).
[src:raku-lang/metaprogramming] One usage of metaprogramming is to instrument programs in order to do dynamic program analysis.
[src:raku-lang/metaprogramming] Some argue that there is a sharp learning curve to make complete use of metaprogramming features.
[src:raku-lang/metaprogramming] Since metaprogramming gives more flexibility and configurability at runtime, misuse or incorrect use of metaprogramming can result in unwarranted and unexpected errors that can be extremely difficult to debug to an average developer.
[src:raku-lang/metaprogramming] It can introduce risks in the system and make it more vulnerable if not used with care.
[src:raku-lang/metaprogramming] Some of the common problems, which can occur due to wrong use of metaprogramming are inability of the compiler to identify missing configuration parameters, invalid or incorrect data can result in unknown exception or different results.
[src:raku-lang/metaprogramming] Due to this, some believe that only high-skilled developers should work on developing features which exercise metaprogramming in a language or platform and average developers must learn how to use these features as part of convention.
[src:raku-lang/metaprogramming] The IBM/360 and derivatives had powerful macro assembler facilities that were often used to generate complete assembly language programs or sections of programs (for different operating systems for instance).
[src:raku-lang/metaprogramming] Macros provided with CICS transaction processing system had assembler macros that generated COBOL statements as a pre-processing step.
[src:raku-lang/metaprogramming] Other assemblers, such as MASM, also support macros.
[src:raku-lang/metaprogramming] Use of dependent types allows proving that generated code is never invalid.
[src:raku-lang/metaprogramming] However, this approach is leading-edge and rarely found outside of research programming languages.
[src:raku-lang/metaprogramming] The list of notable metaprogramming systems is maintained at List of program transformation systems.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] In computer science, **pattern matching** is the act of checking a given sequence of tokens for the presence of the constituents of some pattern.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] In contrast to pattern recognition, the match usually must be exact: "either it will or will not be a match." The patterns generally have the form of either sequences or tree structures.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] Uses of pattern matching include outputting the locations (if any) of a pattern within a token sequence, to output some component of the matched pattern, and to substitute the matching pattern with some other token sequence (i.e., search and replace).
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] Sequence patterns (e.g., a text string) are often described using regular expressions and matched using techniques such as backtracking.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] Tree patterns are used in some programming languages as a general tool to process data based on its structure, e.g.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] C#, F#, Haskell, Java, ML, Python, Racket, Ruby, Rust, Scala, Swift and the symbolic mathematics language Mathematica have special syntax for expressing tree patterns and a language construct for conditional execution and value retrieval based on it.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] Often it is possible to give alternative patterns that are tried one by one, which yields a powerful conditional programming construct.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] Pattern matching sometimes includes support for guards.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] Early programming languages with pattern matching constructs include COMIT (1957), SNOBOL (1962), which introduced pattern matching as a core, first-class language capability for string and text manipulation.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] This paradigm evolved into structured, tree-based data evaluation with Refal (1968), which used pattern matching to manipulate symbolic expressions.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] The concept was soon adapted into logic programming with Prolog (1972), where pattern matching took the form of structural unification to resolve logical queries.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] Functional programming languages rapidly adopted and formalized the feature across the late 1970s and early 1980s, beginning with the St Andrews Static Language (SASL) (1976), NPL (1977), and the Kent Recursive Calculator (KRC) (1981).
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] The pattern matching feature of function arguments in the language ML (1973) and its dialect Standard ML (1983) heavily formalized compile-time exhaustiveness checking.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] This approach has been carried over to some other functional programming languages that were influenced by them, such as Haskell (1990), Scala (2004), and F# (2005).
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] The pattern matching construct with the `match` keyword that was introduced in the ML dialect Caml (1985) was followed by languages such as OCaml (1996), F# (2005), F* (2011), and Rust (2015).
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] Over time, multi-paradigm languages begin implementing algebraic data types and pattern matching natively, culminating in modern implementations like Python's `match-case` syntax (2021) and Java's pattern matching enhancements (2023).
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] Many text editors support pattern matching of various kinds to facilitate advanced search-and-replace capabilities.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] The QED editor, designed by Ken Thompson, was a pioneer in supporting regular expression searching.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] Thompson's implementation of regular expression parsing in QED laid the groundwork for the text search utilities in ed, sed, and grep.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] Furthermore, some versions of the TECO editor supported advanced matching features, including the logical OR operator in searches.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] Computer algebra systems (CAS) generally support pattern matching on algebraic expressions to achieve symbolic simplification and integration.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] Early systems like Macsyma (1968) used semantic pattern matching to recognize algebraic equivalence; for example, its internal engine could successfully match both `3x2 + 4` and `(x + 1)(x + 6)` as occurrences of a "quadratic in x" pattern template.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] Modern computer algebra systems, including Mathematica and Maple, rely heavily on pattern-matching rules to transform user expressions, find analytical solutions to differential equations, and build user-defined simplification frameworks.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] Pattern matching involves specialized terminology.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] Pattern languages can be rich; see below for terminology denoting specific kinds of pattern.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] The value to be examined and matched against a pattern.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] Replacement of a portion of a scrutinee data structure with some computed value.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] The computation may depend on the replaced portion of the scrutinee as well as on other bindings extracted from the scrutinee.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] While some concepts are relatively common to many pattern languages, other pattern languages include unique or unusual extensions.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] that portion when the continuation executes.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] , the wildcard pattern accepts all values without examining them further, ignoring their structure.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] is an expression that must succeed (or yield Boolean true) as a final step before considering a pattern to have successfully matched.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] ), guards are written using a restricted subset of the full language; in others (e.g.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] The predicate is applied to the portion of the scrutinee corresponding to the position of the predicate in the pattern; if the predicate responds with Boolean false, the pattern is considered to have failed.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] to each element; the overall pattern thus succeeds only when the scrutinee is a list of even numbers.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] , where a user-defined function transforms the portion of the scrutinee corresponding to the position of the view pattern before continuing the match.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] View patterns generalize predicate patterns, allowing further matching on the result of the function rather than simply expecting a Boolean value.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] Some pattern languages allow direct comparison of portions of the scrutinee with previously-computed (or constant) data structures.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] In Erlang, mention of any variable already in scope in a pattern causes it to act as a constraint in this way (instead of as a binding).
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] Some languages allow macros in pattern context to allow abstraction over patterns.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] The simplest pattern in pattern matching is an explicit value or a variable.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] Now, whenever f is given 0 as argument the pattern matches and the function returns 1.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] With any other argument, the matching and thus the function fail.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] Here, the first `n` is a single variable pattern, which will match absolutely any argument and bind it to name n to be used in the rest of the definition.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] In Haskell (unlike at least Hope), patterns are tried in order so the first definition still applies in the very specific case of the input being 0, while for any other argument the function returns `n * f (n-1)` with n being the argument.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] The wildcard pattern (often written as `_`) is also simple: like a variable name, it matches any value, but does not bind the value to any name.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] Algorithms for matching wildcards in simple string-matching situations have been developed in a number of recursive and non-recursive varieties.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] More complex patterns can be built from the primitive ones of the previous section, usually in the same way as values are built by combining other values.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] The difference then is that with variable and wildcard parts, a pattern does not build into a single value, but matches a group of values that are the combination of the concrete elements and the elements that are allowed to vary within the structure of the pattern.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] A tree pattern describes a part of a tree by starting with a node and specifying some branches and nodes and leaving some unspecified with a variable or wildcard pattern.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] It may help to think of the abstract syntax tree of a programming language and algebraic data types.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] In Haskell, the following line defines an algebraic data type `Color` that has a single data constructor `ColorConstructor` that wraps an integer and a string.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] The constructor is a node in a tree and the integer and string are leaves in branches.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] When we want to write functions to make `Color` an abstract data type, we wish to write functions to interface with the data type, and thus we want to extract some data from the data type, for example, just the string or just the integer part of `Color`.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] If we pass a variable that is of type Color, how can we get the data out of this variable?
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] The creations of these functions can be automated by Haskell's data record syntax.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] This OCaml example which defines a red–black tree and a function to re-balance it after element insertion shows how to match on a more complex structure generated by a recursive data type.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] The compiler verifies at compile-time that the list of cases is exhaustive and none are redundant.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] Pattern matching can be used to filter data of a certain structure.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] In Mathematica, the only structure that exists is the tree, which is populated by symbols.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] In the traditional, more suitable syntax, the symbols are written as they are and the levels of the tree are represented using `[]`, so that for instance `a[b,c]` is a tree with a as the parent, and b and c as the children.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] A pattern in Mathematica involves putting "_" at positions in that tree.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] will match elements such as A[1], A[2], or more generally A[*x*] where *x* is any entity.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] In this case, `A` is the concrete element, while `_` denotes the piece of tree that can be varied.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] A symbol prepended to `_` binds the match to that variable name while a symbol appended to `_` restricts the matches to nodes of that symbol.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] Note that even blanks themselves are internally represented as `Blank[]` for `_` and `Blank[x]` for `_x`.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] Pattern matching applies to the *structure* of expressions.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] because only these elements will match the pattern `a[b[_],_]` above.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] In Mathematica, it is also possible to extract structures as they are created in the course of computation, regardless of how or where they appear.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] The function `Trace` can be used to monitor a computation, and return the elements that arise which match a pattern.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] Then, we can ask the question: Given fib[3], what is the sequence of recursive Fibonacci calls?
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] In symbolic programming languages, it is easy to have patterns as arguments to functions or as elements of data structures.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] A consequence of this is the ability to use patterns to declaratively make statements about pieces of data and to flexibly instruct functions how to operate.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] For instance, the Mathematica function `Compile` can be used to make more efficient versions of the code.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] The Curry–Howard correspondence between proofs and programs relates ML-style pattern matching to case analysis and proof by exhaustion.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] By far the most common form of pattern matching involves strings of characters.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] In many programming languages, a particular syntax of strings is used to represent regular expressions, which are patterns describing string characters.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] However, it is possible to perform some string pattern matching within the same framework that has been discussed throughout this article.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] In Mathematica, strings are represented as trees of root StringExpression and all the characters in order as children of the root.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] Thus, to match "any amount of trailing characters", a new wildcard ___ is needed in contrast to _ that would match only a single character.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] In Haskell and functional programming languages in general, strings are represented as functional lists of characters.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] A functional list is defined as an empty list, or an element constructed on an existing list.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] The structure for a list with some elements is thus `element:list`.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] When pattern matching, we assert that a certain piece of data is equal to a certain pattern.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] We assert that the first element of `head`'s argument is called element, and the function returns this.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] We know that this is the first element because of the way lists are defined, a single element constructed onto a list.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] The empty list would not match the pattern at all, as an empty list does not have a head (the first element that is constructed).
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] will match a string that has two characters and begins with "a".
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] Symbolic entities can be introduced to represent many different classes of relevant features of a string.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] will match a string that consists of a letter first, and then a number.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] The main advantage of symbolic string manipulation is that it can be completely integrated with the rest of the programming language, rather than being a separate, special purpose subunit.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] The entire power of the language can be leveraged to build up the patterns themselves or analyze and transform the programs that contain them.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] SNOBOL (*StriNg Oriented and symBOlic Language*) is a computer programming language developed between 1962 and 1967 at AT&T Bell Laboratories by David J.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] SNOBOL4 stands apart from most programming languages by having patterns as a first-class data type (*i.e.* a data type whose values can be manipulated in all ways permitted to any other data type in the programming language) and by providing operators for pattern concatenation and alternation.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] Strings generated during execution can be treated as programs and executed.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] SNOBOL was quite widely taught in larger US universities in the late 1960s and early 1970s and was widely used in the 1970s and 1980s as a text manipulation language in the humanities.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] Since SNOBOL's creation, newer languages such as AWK and Perl have made string manipulation by means of regular expressions fashionable.
[src:raku-lang/pattern-matching] SNOBOL4 patterns, however, subsume Backus–Naur form (BNF) grammars, which are equivalent to context-free grammars and more powerful than regular expressions.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] The Raku design process was first announced on 19 July 2000, on the fourth day of that year's Perl Conference, by Larry Wall in his *State of the Onion 2000* talk.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] At that time, the primary goals were to remove "historical warts" from the language; "easy things should stay easy, hard things should get easier, and impossible things should get hard"; and a general cleanup of the internal design and application programming interfaces (APIs).
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] The process began with a series of Request for Comments (RFCs).
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] This process was open to all contributors, and left no aspect of the language closed to change.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Once the RFC process was complete, Wall reviewed and classified each of the 361 requests received.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] He then began the process of writing several "Apocalypses", using the original meaning of the term, "revealing".
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] While the original goal was to write one Apocalypse for each chapter of *Programming Perl*, it became obvious that, as each Apocalypse was written, previous Apocalypses were being invalidated by later changes.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] For this reason, a set of Synopses was published, each one relating the contents of an Apocalypse, but with any subsequent changes reflected in updates.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Today, the Raku specification is managed through the "roast" testing suite, while the Synopses are kept as a historical reference.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] There is also a series of Exegeses written by Damian Conway that explain the content of each Apocalypse in terms of practical usage.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Each Exegesis consists of code examples along with a discussion of the usage and implications of the examples.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] There are three primary methods of communication used in the development of Raku today.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] The first is the Raku Internet Relay Chat (IRC) channel on Libera Chat.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] The third is the Git source code repository hosted at GitHub.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] The major goal Wall suggested in his initial speech was the removal of historical warts.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] These included the confusion surrounding sigil usage for containers, the ambiguity between the `select` functions, and the syntactic impact of bareword filehandles.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] There were many other problems that Perl programmers had discussed fixing for years, and these were explicitly addressed by Wall in his speech.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] An implication of these goals was that Perl 6 would not have backward compatibility with the existing Perl codebase.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] This meant that some code which was correctly interpreted by a Perl 5 compiler would not be accepted by a Perl 6 compiler.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Since backward compatibility is a common goal when enhancing software, the breaking changes in Perl 6 had to be stated explicitly.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] The distinction between Perl 5 and Perl 6 became so large that eventually Perl 6 was renamed Raku.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] The language's mascot is "Camelia, the Raku bug".
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Her name is a nod to the camel mascot associated with Perl, and her form, in the pun-loving tradition of the Perl community, is a play on "software bug".
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Spiral designs embedded in her butterfly-like wings resemble the characters "P6", the favored nickname for Perl 6, and off-center eye placement is an intentional pun on "Wall-eyed".
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] One of the goals behind the lively and colorful design of the logo was to discourage misogyny in the community and for it to be an opportunity for those of "masculine persuasion" to show their sensitive side.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] As of 2017, only the Rakudo implementation is under active development.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Rakudo Perl 6 targets a number of virtual machines, such as MoarVM, the Java Virtual Machine, and JavaScript.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] MoarVM is a virtual machine built especially for Rakudo and the NQP Compiler Toolchain.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] There is a layer between Raku and the virtual machines named Not Quite Perl 6 (NQP), which implements Raku rules for parsing Raku, and an abstract syntax tree and backend-specific code generation.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Large portions of Rakudo are written in Raku, or in its subset NQP.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Rakudo is not a completely self-hosting implementation, nor are there concrete plans at this point to make Rakudo a bootstrapping compiler.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Pugs was an initial implementation of Perl 6 written in Haskell, led by Audrey Tang.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Pugs used to be the most advanced implementation of Perl 6.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] As of mid-2007, it is mostly dormant, with updates made only to track the latest version of the Glasgow Haskell Compiler (GHC).
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] As of November 2014, Pugs is unmaintained.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] In 2007, v6-MiniPerl6 ("mp6") and its reimplementation, v6-KindaPerl6 ("kp6") were written as a means to bootstrap the Perl-6.0.0 STD, using Perl 5.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] The STD is a full grammar for Perl 6 and is written in Perl 6.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Yapsi was a Perl 6 compiler and runtime written in Perl 6.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] As a result, it required an existing Perl 6 interpreter, such as one of the Rakudo Star releases, to run.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Niecza, another major Perl 6 implementation effort, focused on optimization and efficient implementation research.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] It targets the Common Language Infrastructure.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] The Raku specification requests that modules be identified by name, version, and authority.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] It is possible to load only a specific version of a module, or even two modules of the same name that differ in version or authority.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] As a convenience, aliasing to a short name is provided.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] CPAN, the Perl module distribution system, does not yet handle Raku modules.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Instead a prototype module system is in use.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Perl and Raku differ fundamentally, though in general the intent has been to "keep Raku Perl", so that Raku is clearly "a Perl programming language".
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Most of the changes are intended to normalize the language, to make it easier for novice and expert programmers alike to understand, and to make "easy things easier and hard things more possible".
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] A major non-technical difference between Perl and Raku is that Raku began as a specification.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] This means that Raku can be re-implemented if needed, and it also means that programmers do not have to read the source code for the ultimate authority on any given feature.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] In contrast, in Perl, the official documentation is not considered authoritative and only describes the behavior of the actual Perl interpreter informally.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Any discrepancies found between the documentation and the implementation may lead to either being changed to reflect the other, a dynamic which drives the continuing development and refinement of the Perl releases.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] In Raku, the dynamic type system of Perl has been augmented by the addition of static types.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Raku offers a gradual typing system, whereby the programmer may choose to use static typing, use dynamic typing, or mix the two.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Perl defines subroutines without formal parameter lists at all (though simple parameter counting and some type checking can be done using Perl's "prototypes").
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Subroutine arguments passed in are aliased into the elements of the array `@_`.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] If the elements of `@_` are modified, the changes are reflected in the original data.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Raku introduces true formal parameters to the language.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] As in Perl, the formal parameters (i.e., the variables in the parameter list) are aliases to the actual parameters (the values passed in), but by default, the aliases are constant so they cannot be modified.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] They may be declared explicitly as read-write aliases for the original value or as copies using the `is rw` or `is copy` directives respectively should the programmer require them to be modified locally.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Raku provides three basic modes of parameter passing: positional parameters, named parameters, and slurpy parameters.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Positional parameters are the typical ordered list of parameters that most programming languages use.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] All parameters may also be passed by using their name in an unordered way.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Named-only parameters (indicated by a `:` before the parameter name) can only be passed by specifying its name, i.e. it never captures a positional argument.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Slurpy parameters (indicated by an `*` before the parameter name) are Raku's tool for creating variadic functions.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] A slurpy hash will capture remaining passed-by-name parameters, whereas a slurpy array will capture remaining passed-by-position parameters.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Positional parameters, such as those used above, are always required unless followed by `?` to indicate that they are optional.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Named parameters are optional by default, but may be marked as required by adding `!` after the variable name.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Slurpy parameters are *always* optional.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Parameters can also be passed to arbitrary blocks, which act as closures.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] This is how, for example, `for` and `while` loop iterators are named.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] In the following example, a list is traversed, 3 elements at a time, and passed to the loop's block as the variables, `$a, $b, $c`.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] This is generally referred to as a "pointy sub" or "pointy block", and the arrow behaves almost exactly like the `sub` keyword, introducing an anonymous closure (or anonymous subroutine in Perl terminology).
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] However, this conceptual mapping breaks down when using references, since they may refer to data structures even though they are scalars.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] This complexity has no equivalent either in common use of natural language or in other programming languages, and it causes high cognitive load when writing code to manipulate complex data structures.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Perl supports object-oriented programming via a mechanism known as *blessing*.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Any reference can be blessed into being an object of a particular class.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] A blessed object can have methods invoked on it using the "arrow syntax" which will cause Perl to locate or "dispatch" an appropriate subroutine by name, and call it with the blessed variable as its first argument.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] While extremely powerful, it makes the most common case of object orientation, a struct-like object with some associated code, unnecessarily difficult.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] In addition, because Perl can make no assumptions about the object model in use, method invocation cannot be optimized very well.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] In the spirit of making the "easy things easy and hard things possible", Raku retains the blessing model and supplies a more robust object model for the common cases.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] The dot replaces the arrow in a nod to the many other languages (e.g.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] C++, Java, Python, etc.) that have coalesced around dot as the syntax for method invocation.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] In the terminology of Raku, `$.x` is called an "attribute".
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Some languages call these *fields*or *members*.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] The method used to access an attribute is called an "accessor".
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] An auto-accessor method is a method created automatically and named after the attribute's name, as the method `x` is in the example above.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] These accessor functions return the value of the attribute.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] When a class or individual attribute is declared with the `is rw` modifier (short for "read/write"), the auto-accessors can be passed a new value to set the attribute to, or it can be directly assigned to as an lvalue (as in the example).
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Auto-accessors can be replaced by user-defined methods, should the programmer desire a richer interface to an attribute.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Attributes can only be accessed directly from within a class definition via the `$!` syntax regardless of how the attributes are declared.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] All other access must go through the accessor methods.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] The Raku object system has inspired the Moose framework that introduces many of Raku's OOP features to Perl.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Inheritance is the technique by which an object or type can re-use code or definitions from existing objects or types.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] For example, a programmer may want to have a standard type but with an extra attribute.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Inheritance in other languages, such as Java, is provided by allowing Classes to be sub-classes of existing classes.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Raku provides for inheritance via Classes, which are similar to Classes in other languages, and Roles.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Roles in Raku take on the function of *interfaces* in Java, *mixins* in Ruby, and *traits* in PHP and in the Smalltalk variant Squeak.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] These are much like classes, but they provide a safer composition mechanism.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] These are used to perform composition when used with classes rather than adding to their inheritance chain.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Roles define nominal types; they provide semantic names for collections of behavior and state.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] The fundamental difference between a role and a class is that classes can be instantiated; roles are not.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Although Roles are distinct from Classes, it is possible to write Raku code that directly instantiates a Role or uses a Role as a type object, Raku will automatically create a class with the same name as the role, making it possible to transparently use a role as if it were a class.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Essentially, a role is a bundle of (possibly abstract) methods and attributes that can be added to a class without using inheritance.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] A role can even be added to an individual object; in this case, Raku will create an anonymous subclass, add the role to the subclass, and change the object's class to the anonymous subclass.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] For example, a Dog is a Mammal because dogs inherit certain characteristics from Mammals, such as mammary glands and (through Mammal's parent, Vertebrate) a backbone.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] On the other hand, dogs also may have one of several distinct types of behavior, and these behaviours may change over time.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] For example, a Dog may be a Pet, a Stray (an abandoned pet will acquire behaviours to survive not associated with a pet), or a Guide for the blind (guide dogs are trained, so they do not start life as guide dogs).
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] However, these are sets of additional behaviors that can be added to a Dog.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] It is also possible to describe these behaviors in such a way that they can be usefully applied to other animals, for example, a Cat can equally be a Pet or Stray.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Hence, Dog and Cat are distinct from each other, while both remain within the more general category Mammal.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] So Mammal is a Class and Dog and Cat are classes that inherit from Mammal.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] But the behaviours associated with Pet, Stray, and Guide are Roles that can be added to Classes, or objects instantiated from Classes.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Roles are added to a class or object with the `does` keyword.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] In order to show inheritance from a class, there is a different keyword `is`.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] The keywords reflect the differing meanings of the two features: role composition gives a class the *behavior* of the role, but doesn't indicate that it is truly the *same thing* as the role.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Although roles are distinct from classes, both are types, so a role can appear in a variable declaration where one would normally put a class.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] For example, a Blind role for a Human could include an attribute of type Guide; this attribute could contain a Guide Dog, a Guide Horse, a Guide Human, or even a Guide Machine.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Perl's regular expression and string-processing support has always been one of its defining features.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Since Perl's pattern-matching constructs have exceeded the capabilities of regular language expressions for some time, Raku documentation exclusively refers to them as *regexes*, distancing the term from the formal definition.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Rules are introduced with the `rule` keyword which has a usage quite similar to subroutine definition.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Anonymous rules can also be introduced with the `regex` (or `rx`) keyword, or they can simply be used inline as regexps were in Perl via the `m` (matching) or `s` (substitute) operators.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] In *Apocalypse 5*, Larry Wall enumerated 20 problems with "current regex culture".
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Among these were that Perl's regexes were "too compact and 'cute'", had "too much reliance on too few metacharacters", "little support for named captures", "little support for grammars", and "poor integration with 'real' language".
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Some Perl constructs have been changed in Raku, optimized for different syntactic cues for the most common cases.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Also, the `,` (comma) operator is now a list constructor, so enclosing parentheses are no longer required around lists.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] now makes `@array` an array with exactly the elements '1', '2', '3', and '4'.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] This is treated as if each left-to-right comparison were performed on its own, and the result is logically combined via the `and` operation.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] The code above will not crash by attempting to assign a list of infinite size to the array `@integers`, nor will it hang indefinitely in attempting to expand the list if a limited number of slots are searched.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] This simplifies many common tasks in Raku including input/output operations, list transformations, and parameter passing.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Related to lazy evaluation is the construction of lazy lists using `gather` and `take`, behaving somewhat like generators in languages like Icon or Python.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] `$squares` will be an infinite list of square numbers, but lazy evaluation of the `gather` ensures that elements are only computed when they are accessed.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Raku introduces the concept of *junctions*: values that are composites of other values.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] `|` indicates a value which is equal to either its left- *or* right-hand arguments.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] `&` indicates a value which is equal to both its left- *and* right-hand arguments.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] These values can be used in any code that would use a normal value.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Operations performed on a junction act on all members of the junction equally, and combine according to the junctive operator.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] In comparisons, junctions return a single true or false result for the comparison.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] "`any`" junctions return true if the comparison is true for any one of the elements of the junction.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] "`all`" junctions return true if the comparison is true for all of the elements of the junction.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] In low-level languages, the concept of macros has become synonymous with textual substitution of source-code due to the widespread use of the C preprocessor.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] However, high-level languages such as Lisp pre-dated C in their use of macros that were far more powerful.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] It is this Lisp-like macro concept that Raku will take advantage of.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] The power of this sort of macro stems from the fact that it operates on the program as a high-level data structure, rather than as simple text, and has the full capabilities of the programming language at its disposal.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] A Raku macro definition will look like a subroutine or method definition, and it can operate on unparsed strings, an AST representing pre-parsed code, or a combination of the two.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] In this particular example, the macro is no more complex than a C-style textual substitution, but because parsing of the macro parameter occurs before the macro operates on the calling code, diagnostic messages would be far more informative.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] However, because the body of a macro is executed at compile time each time it is used, many techniques of optimization can be employed.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] It is even possible to eliminate complex computations from resulting programs by performing the work at compile-time.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] In Perl, identifier names can use the ASCII alphanumerics and underscores also available in other languages.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] In Raku, the alphanumerics can include most Unicode characters.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] In addition, hyphens and apostrophes can be used (with certain restrictions, such as not being followed by a digit).
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Using hyphens instead of underscores to separate words in a name leads to a style of naming called "kebab case".
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] The hello world program is a common program used to introduce a language.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] — though there is more than one way to do it.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Quicksort is a well-known sorting algorithm.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Tower of Hanoi is often used to introduce recursive programming in computer science.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] In the history of Raku there were two waves of book writing.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] The first wave followed the initial announcement of Perl 6 in 2000.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Those books reflect the state of the design of the language of that time, and contain mostly outdated material.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] The second wave, that followed the announcement of Version 1.0 in 2015, includes several books that have already been published and some others that are in the process of being written.
[src:raku-lang/raku-programming-language] Also, a book dedicated to one of the first Perl 6 virtual machines, Parrot, was published in 2009.
